        'markdown' => '<p>We are seeking a highly experienced and knowledgeable Java Spring Boot Microservices Senior Developer to join our team. The successful candidate will be responsible for developing and maintaining microservices-based applications using the latest Java technologies and frameworks.</p>
<p>Key Responsibilities:</p>
<ul><li>Design and develop microservices using Java 8 features and the Spring framework.</li><li>Develop event-driven microservices using Kafka or RabbitMQ.</li><li>Build and deploy microservices in a CI/CD environment using Docker.</li><li>Develop and maintain cloud-based applications.</li><li>Participate in code reviews, testing, and debugging of applications.</li><li>Collaborate with other teams to ensure seamless integration of microservices within the system.</li><li>Continuously improve code quality and application performance.</li><li>Keep up-to-date with the latest trends and technologies in Java development.</li><li>Mentor team members in software development principles, patterns, processes, and practices.</li></ul>
<p>Key Requirements:</p>
<ul><li>Bachelor\'s Degree in Computer Science or in a STEM major.</li><li>8+ years of experience as a Java developer.</li><li>5+ years of experience&nbsp;developing microservices using Spring Boot and Java 8 features.﻿</li><li>Significant experience on core features of Spring such as Dependency Injection and Aspect-Oriented Programming, Spring Security</li><li>Experience with event-driven microservices using Kafka or RabbitMQ.</li><li>Strong knowledge of containerization and deploying applications to Docker.</li><li>Experience working in a CI/CD environment.</li><li>Experience with NoSQL Databases (MongoDB, Cassandra, Couchbase, etc.)</li><li>Experience developing cloud-based applications (AWS, Azure, GCP).</li><li>Solid understanding of software development best practices, including Agile methodologies.</li><li>Strong problem-solving and analytical skills.</li><li>Excellent communication and collaboration skills.</li></ul>
<p><br></p>'
